There’s no emotional healing without body stability…

… no matter how that stability looks like for you.

Maybe you wobble in most poses, maybe you think you have zero balance, maybe your ankles and wrists hurt on the floor. It’s all ok!

But! Intentionally building body stability signals to your subtle body that it’s safe.

And this is HUGE.

We often underestimate the effect of safety on a system - nervous, physical, immune.

Safety comes with many things, and a lot of them take years to cultivate within yourself and with others.

But I’m more interested in approaching it from the space of the body.

What if we could jumpstart and accelerate our own safety building though working with the body in a directed and purposeful way?

See, the body, the mind, the soul (or whatever you like to call it), all communicate with each other constantly. So much so that they are totally intertwined into a web of togetherness.

If the body feels tension, the mind interprets tension.

If the body feels safety, the mind interprets safety.

But just how is that safety felt?

To me, and I’m sure others have their own opinions on this, safety is cultivated by trusting in your own resources and strength.

And amazingly, those can easily be built by training the body.

More mindful strength, more range, more freedom. And it all equals more stability, which I like to think leads to more safety.

And once the body is safe, you can be safer, because your body is you.

I would love to know how you view safety and what it means for you. Let me know in the comments!

The Jaw and the Hips: A Love Story ❤️‍🔥

Lots of students in my Hips Like Honey program are also chronic jaw clenchers and teeth grinders (I was too!), and it’s not a coincidence.

The body is a perfectly interconnected web of fascia and communication matter.

Fascia is your connective tissue which wraps around your body connecting every single cell, muscle, organ, and nerve. If one part at one end moves, EVERYTHING moves!

Now for the juicy part: It turns out that one specific fascial line can be traced all the way from the jaw down to your pelvis, establishing a clear connection between the two.

Crazily enough, the way we were able to prove this is by having people speak with different voice tones under full body ultrasound.

When they spoke with a low tone (which is when the jaw feels relaxed), the pelvic floor lengthened and relaxed.

When they spoke with a high pitch tone (which is when the jaw clenches, you can try this), the pelvic floor elevated and contracted.

Nothing in your body is separate. Knowing this direct connection between jaw and hip tension, you can begin working on releasing both.

Are you a jaw clencher or teeth grinder? And if so, how are your hips? Let me know in the comments 👇

I've come to realize that we’ve got things a little bit wrong.

See, we split everything into two opposing categories- good versus bad, pleasant versus unpleasant, easy versus hard.

And we’ve come to equate one side as something we want, and the other side as something we very much don’t want.

Now where’s the issue in that?

Can’t we have our likes and dislikes and shouldn’t we try to avoid hurtful situations?

Isn’t that what life is about?

Yes, it is.

But the level of clinging to the side we want, and resisting the side we don’t is what makes it a problem.

Because the moment we resist is the moment we feel unsafe.

It’s the moment we lose trust.

But what if we looked at all experiences, whether good or bad, as powerful affirmations of our safety?

What if every emotion, whether it's fear, anger, grief, or sadness, was a testament to our inherent security.

I've learned that feeling these emotions doesn't signify danger, but rather highlights my ability to embrace and navigate life's ever-changing landscapes.

Often, we associate safety solely with a lack of risk or threat.

We believe that feeling anything other than joy or contentment implies vulnerability or imminent harm.

But that’s a one sided look at life, which is in the end, always a two sided coin.

Our emotions are not threats to our well-being; they are gateways to self-discovery and growth.

You are safe enough to experience it all!

💙 The new world mantra is:

"I am safe enough to feel this."

❤️‍🔥 THE POWER OF EMOTIONAL EXPRESSION

Let’s talk about something rather odd in this society that will have you suppress most of your emotions for the sake of strength, poise, and culture.

Your body is hardwired to express – joy, anger, sadness, excitement – it doesn't discriminate.

Your body doesn't label feelings as 'good' or 'bad'; it just knows them as feelings, meant to be felt and expressed.

So get out of the habit of beating yourself up for experiencing what you might call 'bad' emotions?

They're as valid as the 'good' ones.

And they don’t mean you are a bad person, or a weak person.

They mean you are A person.

Each emotion has a purpose.

None of them exist in isolation, and once you begin untangling their meaning, you will arrive at your truest essence.

The FULLEST expression of YOU.

In fact, when you give yourself the permission to express these so-called 'bad' emotions, something incredible happens.

The weight they carry, the hold they have over you, begins to dissipate.

It's like opening a window to let fresh air in, allowing these emotions to flow rather than stagnate.

So, the next time you feel anger, sadness, frustration – express them.

Talk about them, write about them, paint them – let them out.

It's not about dwelling in negativity; it's about acknowledging the fullness of your emotional landscape.

By giving yourself the freedom to express, you're practicing emotional liberation.

You're telling yourself that it's okay to be human, to experience the full spectrum of what it means to feel.

You're creating space for growth, healing, and transformation.

Remember, expressing your emotions doesn't diminish your strength; it amplifies it.

It's a sign of resilience, authenticity, and a deep connection with yourself.

What emotion have you been suppressing lately?

Let’s get something straight…

You don't find calm; you return to it.

Even if you can’t remember ever being truly calm, trust me, CALM is who you are.

And it's not about acquiring a new skill or seeking external solutions; it's about remembering the inherent peace that's always within you.

Yes, even now.

Yes, even when you’re in the middle of an argument.

Yes, even when you’re having a panic attack.

IT. IS.THERE.

Think about it like this...

Your mind is like a clear pond, and calm is its natural state.

Yet life's ripples – stress, worries, and distractions – create a fog that obscures this tranquility, and creates a rough surface that makes you forget you were ever calm in the first place.

But what if that fog cleared, and what if the ripples stopped?

You are still that peaceful pond.

THAT is you!

Everything else is just an add on.

The ultimate mindset shift lies here – remember you're not striving for something distant and new.

You’re coming back to your own center.

So how do you make this shift?

🤍 Step 1: Pause and Breathe:

When life gets chaotic, pause for a moment.

Take a deep breath and remind yourself that within you, there's a calm oasis waiting to be rediscovered. Inhale the possibilities, exhale the clutter.

🤍 Step 2: Unravel the Knots:

Identify the mental knots that keep you from your calm.

Is it overthinking?

Is it the need to control everything?

Slowly, start loosening these knots.

🤍 Step 3: Return to Your Center:

Just like a compass always points north, your inner compass points to calm.

Trust it.

Whenever you feel lost in the chaos, come back to your breath, your stillness, your center.

It's a shift that changes everything.

You're not adding more to your plate; you're carving out space for the calm that's already there.

As you shed the layers of tension and worry, you'll realize that the journey is about rediscovering, not reinventing.

It's like coming home to a place you never truly left.

Let’s talk about Savasana guilt 🙄

That feeling that creeps in when you can't completely switch off, when your mind drifts, and that inner dialogue starts critiquing your supposed "failure" to fully relax.

The truth is, Savasana isn't always an instant ticket to zen.

It's okay if your mind races like a caffeinated squirrel during those moments of stillness.

Contrary to popular belief, Savasana isn't about achieving a perfectly blank mind; it's about allowing yourself to simply be. ⁣

In a world that values productivity and constant hustle, it's understandable that lying still might trigger some discomfort.

We're wired to be on the go, to multitask, to conquer to-do lists.

So, the idea of lying down and just being present can be challenging—even intimidating. ⁣

But that's precisely why Savasana is a vital part of your practice.

It's a moment of radical self-care, a time to let go of expectations, and a space to embrace whatever thoughts or sensations arise.

It's not about perfection; it's about acceptance.⁣

So, the next time you find yourself in Savasana, remember that it's okay if your mind is a swirling vortex of thoughts.

It's okay if you don't feel an instant surge of calm.

Give yourself permission to experience this pose in your own unique way.

As you lie there, allowing your body to melt into the mat, you're still benefiting from the relaxation response that Savasana triggers in your nervous system.⁣

Free yourself from the pressure to be "perfectly zen" during Savasana.

Instead, celebrate the moments when you can quiet the mental chatter, and forgive yourself for those times when you can't.

After all, yoga isn't about attaining perfection; it's about embracing the journey, quirks and all.

What goes through your mind when in savasana? ⁣

Ahhh, the myth of the "perfect alignment." ⁣

Let’s dive in shall we?

I for one think alignment should be fluid.

Because to me, the pursuit of textbook-perfect alignment in every yoga pose is far from the golden ticket to a fulfilling practice.

And isn’t that what we are after in the end?

In fact, fixating on aligning every inch of your body can sometimes lead to more frustration than growth. ⁣

We've all been there—obsessing over the angle of our hips, the alignment of our heels, or the curvature of our spine, all in the name of nailing the "right" posture.

While alignment cues are invaluable, it's essential to remember that every body is unique.

What might look perfect on one yogi might not be the best fit for YOU.

The emphasis on perfect alignment can inadvertently push us into self-criticism and discourage exploration.

And guess what?

Yoga IS about exploration.

So how would it feel like to liberate yourself from the rigid confines of textbook alignment?

What if you prioritized how the pose felt in your body instead?

If a micro-adjustment feels natural and serves your body well, great!

But if you find that a slight variation brings you more comfort and allows you to soften more, that’s where YOUR pose lies.

Remember, yoga is a balance between discipline and self-compassion.

It's about honoring your body's unique architecture while moving mindfully.

So the next time you flow into a pose, give yourself permission to embrace your personal alignment.

Feel the pose, breathe through it, and listen to your body's wisdom. ⁣

Let's ditch the pursuit of perfection and move authentically instead!

How many times a day do you catch yourself clenching your jaw, tensing your belly, or holding your pelvic floor?

I’ll go first: A LOT!

And I’ve been doing the work I’m doing for yearsss, teaching my nervous system how to downregulate, and yet, I still have to remind myself DAILY to stop clenching.

STOP CLENCHING!

Ah, such simple yet such difficult advice.

This society makes us protective.

It makes us scared and untrusting, and the body responds to that by shrinking, bracing, and closing.

Most of the time when you clench, you don’t even realize you do.

It becomes your status quo and it’s really hard to break that habit if it does.

So the first step is to START NOTICING the clenching.

Clenching is your body’s reflex to stress, anxiety, or even just the rush of everyday life.

But by becoming aware of these subconscious contractions and consciously releasing them, you can experience immediate relief you didn't even know you needed.

✨ Let Go of the Jaw

Let your teeth part, and imagine your jaw muscles softening.

It's incredible how much tension we store in our jaw without realizing it.

✨ Relax the Belly

Place one hand on your belly and take a slow, deep breath in.

As you exhale, consciously release any tightness you feel in your abdominal muscles.

Let your belly expand naturally with each breath.

✨ Release the Pelvic Floor

While sitting or standing, gently engage your pelvic floor muscles by imagining you're trying not to pee.

Now, as you exhale, consciously release this engagement.

It's like a mini-reset for your pelvic muscles.

Embracing these small practices throughout your day can bring about a world of difference.

Remember, the places where you contract are also the places where you can experience profound liberation.

So, give yourself the gift of awareness and release – you deserve it.

Let your body breathe, let your muscles ease, and let your being rediscover a sense of true openness.
